!! Summary

This adventure pits Arien against the [[Iron Circle]], a company of cruel mercenaries that has seized control of the county of [[Harkenwold]]. Arien must become a daring rebel and lead the folk of her home county against their oppressors.

At present, [[Iron Circle]] mercenaries are plundering the land. Count [[Alben ir'Clarn]] has left for the season on holiday to [[Wroat]], leaving his castellan [[Jonn Stockmer]] in charge; however, the castellan is now a prisoner in his own keep, and a villainous lord named [[Nazin Redthorn]] rules in his place. The Harkenwold folk are down to their last hope—that a brave hero will answer their calls for help and break the Iron Circle.

!! Background

About six weeks ago, [[Nazin Redthorn]] led his band of mercenaries known as the [[Iron Circle]] into [[Harkenwold]] in a surprise attack. The brigands stormed the [[Harkenton]] [[Keep|Harken Keep]] and took the [[castellan|Jonn Stockmer]] captive. Iron Circle sweeps and raids soon quelled any show of resistance, leaving the county a conquered land. The Iron Circle has bribed the [[Municipal Guard|Breland Municipal Guard]] of Harkenton to prevent couriers, messengers, or anyone who might be a threat from leaving or entering the county by main roads. (Everyday commoners, merchants, and farmers are allowed to come and go, but they are questioned first, and subjected to heavy tolls.) The mercenaries are also forcing a [[Sivis]] [[stonespeaker|speaking stone]] to answer any messages from the Count with false, mundane replies. 

The new bandit "authorities" are pillaging Harkenwold through "tolls" and confiscations, harshly punishing anyone who resists. [[Nazin|Nazin Redthorn]] is further strengthening his hold by negotiating with other malignant forces. In particular, he's used some of the loot he's plundered from the county's suffering populace to buy the friendship of a group of odious [[bullywug]]s.

The Iron Circle hasn't completely locked down the county; they want to avoid too much attention, and prevent the local populace from panicking. So they allow a small degree of movement in and out of the region, especially for merchants and entertainers—though they demand heavy tolls at checkpoints on the main roads, manned by bribed [[Municipal Guards|Breland Municipal Guard]]. However, any individuals who might pose a threat, such as suspected spies or agents of the government, are detained or possibly eliminated. Despite these measures, [[Nazin Redthorn]] knows that this operation is short-term, and that their hold on this region won't last forever. But he believes that by the time word reaches the Count's ears and he returns with an army, the [[Iron Circle]] will have withdrawn and escaped, having bled the county dry.

!! Hook

[[Arien Grimbold]] hasn't been home to [[Mistmarsh]] since she left for [[Starilaskur]] almost a year ago. She's been in regular contact with her parents via letters, but she hasn't received a letter from them (or anyone else in Mistmarsh) in a while. She sends them a letter telling them that she swore a [[paladin]] oath and graduated from novicehood... and still no response. So she decides to go back to her home town. ([[Roak]] says he needs to stay in [[Starilaskur]] because the [[Brightblade]] festival is coming up, and he needs to compete!)

!! Freeing Harkenwold

To successfully overthrow the [[Iron Circle]] and restore freedom to [[Harkenwold]], Arien must accomplish at least four of the following goals:

* Defeat the [[bullywug]]s of the <<scrollToHeader "Toadwallow Caverns">>.
* Forge an alliance with <<scrollToHeader "the Cliffwalker Shifters">>.
* Win <<scrollToHeader "the Battle of Mistmarsh">>.
* Rescue Castellan [[Stockmer|Jonn Stockmer]] from <<scrollToHeader "Harken Keep">>.
* Defeat [[Nazin Redthorn]], the leader of the [[Iron Circle]].

Achieving four of these goals ensures that the Harkenwolders eventually triumph over the [[Iron Circle]]. Achieving all five brings about an immediate victory. For example, losing the Battle of Mistmarsh would be a serious setback, but the remaining villages can beat the Iron Circle if Nazin is dead, the castellan is freed, the Cliffwalkers are on their side, and the bullywugs pose no threat.

Note that [[Nazin Redthorn]] is an arrogant and overconfident man; he is willing to let resistance gather over time, so that he can crush it all at once when it suits him.

!! Travel to Mistmarsh

The trip from [[Starilaskur]] to [[Heeson's Ferry]] via [[lightning rail]] takes about six hours. When Arien disembarks at Heeson's Ferry, she needs to make her way south. No [[Lyrandar]] riverboats make their way upriver these days, since they typically wait until Gatherhunt at the end of [[Barrakas]]. Keelboats (poleboats) make the journey up and down the [[Yedan River]], but it's slow going upstream; they only average 15 miles per day. It's faster (and cheaper) to trek on foot or by horse. The major villages are noted on the map, but every few miles, she can find little steadings: farms or homesteads in the countryside surrounded by many acres of land, home to a single extended family (no more than 20 people).

[[Heeson's Ferry]] to [[Pran]] is about 145 miles (or 157 miles by river). If Arien walks or takes a horse (30 miles per day), that should take 5 days (6 days to [[Mistmarsh]]) Really hustling, the horse can go up to 60 miles in a day, but will need to rest a day or two to recover. If she takes a keelboat, it should take 10.5 days (12 days to Mistmarsh). When she reaches [[Nelview]] (53 miles south of Heeson's Ferry, 2 days journey), she starts to realize something is afoot; rumors circulate that brigands have taken over the entire county to the south, that people aren't allowed out or in along the main roads, including [[Couriers Guild]] mail carriers.

Pran is the last village before she'll need to travel off the main road to avoid attention; a group of [[Municipal Guards|Breland Municipal Guard]] from [[Harkenton]] have set up a checkpoint on the main road heading south. Someone in Pran might mention that there's been some kind of change in leadership down south, and it's getting to be too expensive to travel there; the tolls are too high. The guards at the checkpoint mumble something about an ongoing security risk that's under active investigation. They check Arien's [[traveling papers]] and ask about her intentions for visiting the area. (The Guards won't resort to violence; they aren't paid enough for that. They will, however, make contact with the Iron Circle if Arien makes a scene or appears suspicious.)

[[Pran]] to [[Mistmarsh]] is 24 miles along the main road, or longer off-road—another day of travel. On this journey, she encounters the [[Iron Circle]] for the first time: Earlene's farmstead.

!! Earlene's Plight

Rounding a bend in the road, Arien spies a pillar of smoke climbing into the sky. The source, hidden by thick trees, is about a mile west of the main road, along a dirt path. When she investigates, she sees human brigands with an attack dog surrounding a farmhouse. The humans all wear black cloaks with a gray ring emblem. They're preparing pitch-soaked torches, laughing and taunting whoever's inside. They've already burned a small outbuilding—the source of the smoke column.

The ruffians are focused on the farmhouse, so it isn't too difficult to sneak up on them. A four-foot-high fieldstone wall surrounds the property. If alerted, the brigands attempt to scare Arien off. The dog growls, and one of the men scowls and waves his arm. "Move on, you!" he snarls. "This is [[Iron Circle]] business!"

From inside the farmhouse, Arien hears a woman's voice shout for help.

''Fight!'' Three brigands and a dog. Each of the brigands has a [[SAC-12]] [[crossbow]] and a shortsword, and is wearing leather armor. When only one brigand remains, he breaks off and tries to run for it. Earlene and her sons hide inside the farmhouse until the fight is over; the Iron Circle bandits ignore them.

''Features of the Area:''

* ''Wall:'' A four-foot-high fieldstone wall surrounds the property.
* ''Burned Outbuilding:'' The thatch roof on this storage shed is burned away, and the walls are charred and weakened, but it is mostly intact.
* ''Farmhouse:'' The windows are shuttered, and the door is barred.
* ''Tree:'' A single tree in the yard provides some cover.
* ''Well:'' A 15-foot-deep well sits on the right end of the property, surrounded by a low stone wall.

When Arien defeats or drives off the [[Iron Circle]] attackers, Earlene emerges from her house, drawing back the heavy bolt and opening the farmhouse door. She looks to be a [[Khoravar|half-elf]] woman of middle years, and two boys of fifteen or so follow after her. The woman looks around the yard, frowning at the bloodshed, and sighs.

"Thank you, stranger," she says. "Those Iron Circle jackals came to rob us. I barred my door, but they said they'd burn the house down with me and my boys in it. You saved our lives—but who are you?"

Earlene is a tough, frontier woman, bowed but unbroken. Talking about the Iron Circle makes her furious.

Questions Arien might ask:

* ''Who are you?'' "My name is Earlene, and these are my sons Jarek and Jarl. This is our farm. Those Iron Circles killed my husband Karthen when they invaded, and my boys and I have been trying to get by ever since."
* ''Who attacked you? Who is the Iron Circle?'' "The Iron Circle is a bunch of mercenaries what fought in the war, but I guess got bored in peacetime and decided to take over this whole county. Count [[Alben|Alben ir'Clarn]] is with his daddy up in [[Wroat]], meantime those jackals took over the keep in [[Harkenton]] over a month ago, and they've been plunderin' and lootin' ever since. They say they're collecting taxes, but they're just robbin' folks, pure and simple."
* ''How can I help?'' "I hear there's some folk tryin' to drum up a rebellion, you ought to head down to [[Mistmarsh]] and talk to old Curlot. He'll know what needs doing. But be careful, and don't go tellin' anyone I told you that."
* ''Where should I go?'' "I'd avoid [[Harkenton]]. It's crawlin' with [[Iron Circle]] brutes. Mistmarsh should be safe enough, for now."
* ''Good-bye.'' "Take care, stranger! My boys and I will hide these bodies; we don't want the ruffians to learn what happened here any time soon."

!! Arriving in Mistmarsh

[[Mistmarsh]] itself is much as Arien left it; the [[Iron Circle]] does not have a strong presence here, as of yet. But worry and fear can be seen in the faces of everyone in town. Arien can make her way to her parents' place, where they have a teary reunion. [[Vylae]] wants Arien to help with the resistance, and suggests going to [[Tor's Hold]] to deal with the [[bullywug]] problem there. At Grem Stables, Arien can speak with [[Curlot Grem]], who suggests attacking [[Iron Circle]] supply caravans (see <<scrollToHeader "Waylay the Caravan">>).

!! Encounters

!!! Tavern Brawl

This encounter happens whenever Arien chooses to seek out and confront some of the [[Iron Circle]] soldiers garrisoning one of the villages in Harkenwold. For example:

* Arien arrives in Mistmarsh and goes to the [[Happy Mallard Inn]] before speaking to [[Curlot Grem]] or [[Vylae]]
* Arien ventures to [[Harkenton]] and stumbles on Iron Circle soldiers in a tavern there
* Arien seeks out a place where Iron Circle soldiers gather together and are off their guard (possibly in [[Larnsville]] or [[Dry Rise]]).
* The soldiers may barge into any tavern where Arien is seeking rest in a town.

This small tavern is occupied by a band of five human soldiers wearing black cloaks with a gray circle emblem. They are loudly harassing the taverner and the barmaid, who is shakily pouring them tankards of ale; one of the brigands rummages around behind the bar, looking for something valuable enough to steal. Several other patrons, common folk, keep their heads down and try not to catch the soldiers' notice.

The brigands sit up and take note of Arien as she enters. "Now who the devil do you think you are?" one of them snarls when he sees her. (if she's armed:) "No one in this miserable town's allowed to carry arms! Set 'em down if you know what's good for you!"

The Iron Circle brigands aren't expecting a fight; when Arien enters the tavern, they sit up and take note (especially if she's obviously armed). They immediately demand an explanation and order her to disarm herself. They don't attack until Arien becomes hostile or fails to comply with their demands. It's possible she can convince the Iron Circle gang that she's not a threat, or that she's allowed to be armed as she is. In any case, the brigands return to harassing the Harkenwolders—roughing them up, robbing them, and so on—until Arien decides to do something about it.

As before, the mercs are wearing leather armor and have crossbows. Three of them have shortswords, while two have morningstars; one of the sword-wielders has scale armor instead of leather.

If a fight breaks out, the townsfolk flee by the safest route possible, or cower in a corner otherwise. 

!!! Waylay the Caravan

Run this encounter when Arien decides to attack [[Iron Circle]] supply lines in [[Harkenwold]]. It fits best when:

* Arien takes [[Curlot Grem]]'s suggestion for a good ambush opportunity
* Another NPC ([[Agalmar]] in [[Larnsville]], [[Eam Grimbold]] in [[Harkenton]]) suggests an attack against the Iron Circle's supply wagons
* Arien roams the countryside in search of Iron Circle activities to disrupt, and stumble across a supply wagon and guards

No matter how Arien and any allies she has with her encounter the wagon, they have time to set up an ambush. After they're in position, read:

<<<
//A large wagon pulled by a big cart horse creaks along the dusty road. Three Iron Circle soldiers in black cloaks with gray circle emblems plod alongside, while a fourth drives the wagon. One of the soldiers is a [[warforged]], while the rest are human. Another human in chainmail with a dark hood over his head sits near the driver. Unlike the soldiers, he wears a red surcoat, and his circle design is black trimmed in gold.//
<<<

The four brigands (including the warforged) wield crossbows and melee weapons (scimitar, mace, or short sword), and the three human brigands wear leather armor. One has a light shield. The hooded man is a [[wandslinger]] who possesses fiendish power; he can create fiery tendrils that lash out and grab hold of his enemies, and he can cast the spell [[web]] (though it takes the form of black tar). The wandslinger can also place a "dark imperative" on one of his allies once per day, granting them extra defense and adding [[necrotic damage|damage type]] to their attacks.

The driver and wandslinger remain in the wagon. The driver uses his crossbow, and the wandslinger casts spells. If the fight goes badly, one of them lashes the horse's reins, inducing the animal to bolt.

The three brigands on foot melee with Arien and the ambushers, but try to stay close to the wagon. They may move behind the wagon and use it for cover, returning fire with their crossbows. 

The horse doesn't fight. If injured, it bolts, dragging the wagon behind it. This might cause creatures in the wagon to fall out.

A lockbox in the wagon can be opened with a key on the wandslinger's person. Inside the lockbox is [[8 crowns|money]] and an [[elemental gem]] (yellow diamond).

!!! Hunted!

Run this encounter when the adventurers are traveling through [[Harkenwold]] to a new locale or village. It should occur after they have stirred up trouble, such as a couple days after they clean out the <<scrollToHeader "Toadwallow Caverns">>.

Weather plays a vital role in this encounter. In the hours leading up to the event, the overcast sky darkens and a light rain begins to fall. By the time the encounter unfolds, the rain has become heavy, and a chill fog enshrouds the land. This inclement weather makes it harder to see at a distance, and easier to hide from other creatures; it also makes it harder to move quickly on the muddy road.

Because Arien and her companions have proven to be a significant threat to the [[Iron Circle]] by this point, [[Nazin Redthorn]] dispatches roving squads to run her to the ground. Guided by a handful of informers and lucky guesswork, one such squad comes across Arien as she's traveling across the county.

Read:

<<<
//You've been traveling for hours through heavy rain, and the muddy ground clings to your boots. A few miles from your goal, through the fog you spot an Iron Circle brigand holding a lantern and riding a large, fierce tiger. The tiger roars, and two more brigands with crossbows emerge from behind some nearby trees to the left of the path. Their leader, a malicious-looking [[gnome]] woman in a red surcoat, stands between them.//

//"There she is!" the woman shouts. "Take her!"//
<<<

The three brigands are similarly outfitted to Iron Circle soldiers Arien has already faced (leather armor, maybe one has mail; the one riding a tiger has a scimitar.) The tiger is a trained war mount—unusual, but not unheard of among the Brelish military. The gnome woman is a [[wandslinger]] who possesses fiendish power; she can create fiery tendrils that lash out and grab hold of her enemies, and she can cast the spell [[web]] (though it takes the form of black tar). The wandslinger can also place a "dark imperative" on one of her allies once per day, granting them extra defense and adding [[necrotic damage|damage type]] to their attacks.

The tiger and its rider charge Arien or the nearest enemy; the tiger rakes with its claws while the rider slices with his scimitar. The other two brigands fire their crossbows, peppering her and her party with bolts for 15 or so seconds before advancing. The wandslinger prefers to remain at range, using her fiery tendrils. She saves her "dark imperative" for the tiger or its rider.

!!! Toadwallow Caverns

Located beneath a cluster of forested hills overlooking fetid marshland, the Toadwallow Caverns are unpleasant and ill-regarded. The caverns are named for the unusual number of large, deep-throated amphibians that lurk in the boggy land nearby.

One of the Toadwallow caves is currently occupied by the Mud-Hides, a tribe of [[bullywug]]s that moved into the area a few months ago. The chieftain ''Gloorpk'' struck a deal with the [[Iron Circle]]—as long as he follows [[Nazin Redthorn]]'s orders, his clan is free to raid and plunder the surrounding area. The Mud-Hides have also been gifted weapons they wouldn't otherwise have access to, such as [[SAC-12]] [[crossbow]]s.

The Toadwallow Caverns share a few common characteristics:

* Glowing green moss grows throughout the caverns, providing dim light.
* Shallow pools and streams ranging from 2 to 5 feet deep are scattered throughout the caverns. Their rocky bottoms are covered with slippery mud.
* The walls are natural rock, uneven but slick. The floors are level rock covered by a few inches of sand, dry mud, or dirt from old river floods.

Arien finds the region of the Toadwallow Caverns, and uses her tracking skills to identify which cavern houses the [[bullywug]]s.

Read:

<<<
//Water gushes from a cave mouth set into the face of a vine-covered hill, forming a 10-foot-high waterfall that bleeds into a stream. The ground near the base of the hill is spongy, and clouds of insects harangue you.//
<<<

Bullywug sentries sit inside the cave, but aren't very attentive; even a half-hearted attempt to stay quiet allows Arien to surprise the bullywugs. However, if she makes a lot of sound climbing up the ledge, she might alert them, at which point they set up an ambush. 

When she enters the cave, if she hasn't alerted the bullywugs, read:

<<<
//The cave mouth opens into a dank chamber. Water gushes from a hole in the nearby wall, forming a shallow stream that plunges over the ledge behind you. A stagnant pool of water fills a corner to your right, and a thick patch of multicolored fungus grows atop a pile of offal in the middle of the cave. Two froglike humanoid creatures crouch in the shadows behind the fungi, apparently keeping watch. They wear poorly fitting armor made from leather and carry spears.//
<<<

Arien faces off against the two bullywugs at the entrance, and two more that lurk deeper in the cave. After the bullywugs become aware of her, one of them scrambles into a corner and withdraws a [[SAC-12]] [[crossbow]]. Where did he get that?? However, after firing one bolt, the bullywug drops the weapon and resumes using a spear; it seems not to know how to reload the crossbow. One of the two that emerges from deeper in the cave leaps around unpredictably. All of the bullywugs have a rancid air about them, that has a sense of unnatural "wrongness" to it; this feeling of wrongness fades as the bullywugs die.

After Arien dispatches these, she can continue into the cave. When she enters the main cavern, read:

<<<
//A giant dragon's skull dominates this damp, 15-foot-high cave. You see no other remains, suggesting that the skull was brought here from elsewhere. Beyond the great skull, a dribble of water pouring through a crack in the ceiling forms a shallow pool nearly 20 feet across and 10 feet wide.//
<<<

If Arien does well on an investigation attempt, she might see one or more bullywugs hiding in the corners of the room, as well as a particularly fat bullywug hiding inside the dragon skull, peering at her through an eye socket. 

The fat bullywug is Gloorpk, the chieftain of the Mud-Hides tribe. A number of lesser bullywugs attend him constantly, doting on their leader in the hopes of averting his wrath. The bullywugs here are vigilant; it's unlikely Arien will be able to surprise them. They hide upon hearing sounds of combat in the earlier chambers, and will try to surprise Arien when she gets close.

Once Gloorpk's location is revealed, read:

<<<
//A loud croak emanates from inside the dragon skull, and bulbous eyes stare at you from behind one of the hollow eye sockets.//
<<<

As the bullywugs emerge from hiding, Gloorpk croaks from within the skull. He starts with a "vraaaa-kra," which causes a [[gray ooze]] to slither out from a 15-foot-pit in the cave (filled with the bones of past meals) and head towards Arien. (Gray oozes corrode metal.) Gloorpk also emits a "glaaaar-pat," which deals [[psychic damage|damage type]], and possibly a "rooooo-glog," which invigorates all bullywugs within 30 feet. If he's forced outside of the skull, he does his best to squirm back inside.

The other bullywugs are straightforward combatants. There are between 5 and 10 here (use good judgement). Some of them have crude spears, but others have weapons Arien has seen in the hands of [[Iron Circle]] soldiers—scimitars and crossbows.

The pool in the center of the room is a ''breeding pool.'' It is 3 feet deep and contains dozens of translucent bullywug eggs, each the size of a baseball. The eggs are easily destroyed.

As for the dragon skull: it's from an enormous [[black dragon]] who died in the Mistmarsh swamp ages ago. The bullywugs found it nearby and brought it here.

After the fight, as Arien is preparing to leave the bullywug lair, more foul creatures arrive. ''Uggloor'', the champion of the Mud-Hides tribe, has just returned from a raid with a prisoner in tow—a gift to amuse Chieftain Gloorpk. Uggloor croaks loudly as he approaches the cave, to inform the sentries that he has returned. He expects a reply. If Arien (or an ally) isn't able to respond with a similar croaking noise, Uggloor concludes that something is amiss.

When Arien can see the raiding party, read:

<<<
//A hulking bullywug approaches the cave mouth with a fine halberd in one hand and a short rope grasped tightly in the other. The rope ends in a noose around the neck of a ghost-faced [[halfling]] boy who looks fatigued. Two smaller bullywugs with javelins riding a pair of giant frogs accompany them.//
<<<

When he sees Arien or an ally of hers, Uggloor lets go of his prisoner, allowing the halfling boy to run away.

Uggloor is just a big nasty bullywug with a fine-quality spear. He climbs the ledge and charges at the nearest foe. He is overconfident and fights until slain.

The other two leap around on their giant frog mounts; they let Uggloor hold the front line while they hang back and hurl their javelins. The giant frogs might try to lash out with their grasping tongues and pull Arien in. If Uggloor is defeated, they flee.

The boy, ''Heron'', is a 12-year-old member of the [[Reedfoot Clan]]. He and two friends were ambushed by [[bullywug]]s hiding along a muddy shore of the [[White River]]. His friends escaped, but Heron was captured. During the fight, Heron flees at the first opportunity, but he's too tired to get very far. If Arien prevails, he waits for them to emerge from the caves before asking for their help getting back to his clan. If she assists, she loses a half-day of travel time, but earns the gratitude of the Reedfoot halflings.

!!! The Cliffwalker Shifters

The [[Briar Hills]] are a big place, and it might take Arien some time to locate the [[Cliffwalker Camp]]. If she sets out west from [[Dry Rise]], it's about 20 miles to the camp through rising elevation; it might be faster to travel about 18 miles upriver with the help of the [[Reedfoot Clan]], if possible, since the camp is only 4 miles from the river shore.

Read as Arien travels through the hills:

<<<
//The landscape is breathtaking. Rugged hills and deep, river-cut gorges sprawl across the region. The rivers, flowing fresh from the Howling Peaks, slice through the valleys, their murmurs echoing in the natural caverns hidden amongst the hills. The land often suddenly shears away into steep cliffs, revealing stunning vistas of the terrain below and the distant horizon. Abandoned quarries of rusty sandstone are scattered around the landscape, particularly near the [[White River]]; the scars of excavation are softened by time and weather.//

//The vegetation here is sparse. Resilient grasses cling to the rocky soil, providing sustenance to wandering herds of grazing antelope. Deep-green clusters of prickly shrubs are also scattered among the hills.//

//As you pause to gain your bearings, you hear a voice, "Hold there, stranger." A moment later, a [[shifter]] dressed in a short tunic of brown and green steps into the open and advances toward you, a bow in his hand. "I am Minnow of the Cliffwalkers," he says. "I see you are not one of the Iron Circle. Who are you, and what is your business here?"//
<<<

Below his tunic, Minnow is wearing loose-fitting trousers, but no shoes. The skin on his hands and feet seems thick. He has feathers woven into his sideburns, and is wearing a braided grass bracelet adorned with polished yellow stones.

Minnow hears out Arien and then replies, "This is a matter for Grace. Come, follow me." Two more shifters step out of the shadows to join him, and the three hunters lead Arien to a small shifter encampment in a valley by a fresh mountain stream. The shifters seem despondent, or even fearful. There, Minnow introduces Arien to Grace, a shifter woman of middle years with dark eyes, long green-gold hair, and silver jewelry. She is the chief of the Cliffwalker clans.

Grace is reserved and patient. She is willing to let Arien make her case, but she's firmly against the idea of sending her people into someone else's war. She'll want Arien to prove her sincerity by dealing with a problem troubling the Cliffwalkers—a desecrated sanctuary nearby.

Grace speaks slowly and softly. She weighs her words carefully, and often lets a nod or look suffice as an answer to a question.

Questions Arien might ask:

* ''Greetings.'' "You are in great haste, that much is plain. What do you wish of my people?"
* ''Can you help Harkenwold?'' "I grieve for the evil that has come over the land, but it is not our fight."
* ''What about your friends there?'' "Some among the Harkenwolders are indeed our friends, but others ignore or fear us. Would they come to our aid? I doubt it."
* ''If you do nothing, you're next.'' "There could be truth in what you say. In fact, I suspect we have already been afflicted by their evil influence. Still, I deem it better to wait and watch for now. Given time, this Iron Circle may simply move on."
* ''How can I convince you to help?'' "You ask us to risk our lives for you. If you, touched by the divine as you are, were to help us with a particular problem we face, we would be obliged to come to your aid."
* ''What problem are you facing / How has the Iron Circle afflicted you?'' "Not far from here is a sacred site we call the Five Beasts. It's an ancient circle of standing stones, a place where we can connect to our totem spirits. Just over a month ago we arrived here and returned to the site to find it had been desecrated. The stones now weep a black pitch, and the place is suffused with an oppressive energy. Our connection to the primal spirits is severed here. Some fear that unless we move on from here, that we will lose our connection to the beast within. If you can help us cleanse the site, we will be deeply indebted to you."

After speaking with Arien, Grace sets her on the path to the Five Beasts. Grace, Minnow, and two other shifters named Flint and Stripe go with her. The path is rugged; the shifters have no trouble navigating the terrain, but Arien might have trouble. When Arien arrives, she sees the five weathered stones, each ten feet high, carved crudely into the shape of beasts: a bear, a boar, a tiger, a rat, and a wolf. But a thick, hot, black liquid is sweating out of the stones and dripping to the ground; the smell of tar and sulfur is almost overwhelming. In the center of the clearing is a particularly large mound of tar. The stones are also scrawled with unholy symbols.

